segments.text: If it was away, we'd try to get back before night come.
And that was on a Sunday, too, that we done that.
Now, when we were slaves, we couldn't do that, see?
And if we got free, we didn't know nothing to do.
And my mother, she hunted places and bound us out for a dollar a month.
We stayed there maybe a couple of years.
She'd come over and collect the money every month.
And the dollar was worth more then than $10 is now.
And the men used to work for $10 a month, $120 a year, used to hire that way.
Now you can't get a man for $50 a month.
If you pay a man now $50 a month, he don't want to work for it.
More like $50 a week nowadays.
Well, that's just it exactly.
They want $50 a week, and they ain't got no more now.
And we had then, and we, no more money.
But, of course, they bought more stuff and more property and all that.
We didn't have no property.
We didn't have no home.
We had nowhere, nothing.
We didn't have nothing.
We just grew, like your cattle, we just turned out and get along the best you could.
Nobody to look after, so well.
We've been slaves all our lives.
My mother was a slave.
My sister was a slave.
Father was a slave.
Who was your father a slave for?
He was a slave for Burnley.
He belonged to Burnley.
Didn't he belong to Thomas Jefferson at one time?
He didn't belong to Thomas Jefferson.
My grandfather belonged to Thomas Jefferson.
Oh, your grandfather did.
And my father belonged to Burnley.
Burnley died during the war time.
Because he was afraid he'd have to go to war.
But now, in them days, you could hire a substitute to take your place.
Well, he couldn't get a substitute to take his place, so he'd run away from home.
And he took hold.
And when he come back, the war was over, but he died.
And then, if he had lived, it wouldn't have been no good.
The Yankees just come along and...
and just broke the mill open and rolled all the flour out in the river and broke the store open and sold all the meat out in the street and sold all the sugar out.
And we'd boil it and we'd pick it up and carry it and give it to our middle missus and master, young master, and tell them we'd come to be.
Well, I don't know how.
I don't know how to tell you the truth.
When I think of it today, I don't know how I'm living.
None of the rest of them that I know of is living.
I'm the oldest one that I know that's living.
But still, I'm thankful to the Lord.
Now, if my master wanted to send me, he never said you couldn't get a horse and ride and walk, give you a note.
He'd be barefooted and cold.
He wasn't no more than a dog some of them in them days.
He wasn't treated as good as they treat dogs now.
But still, I didn't like to talk with him because it makes people feel bad.
I could say a whole lot I don't like to say.
I won't say a whole lot no more.
Do you remember much about the Civil War?
No, I don't remember much about it.
You were a little young then, I guess.
I remember when the Yankees come along and took all the good horses and took all the, sold all the meat and flour and sugar and stuff out in the river and let it go down the river.
And they know the people wouldn't have nothing to live on, but they done that.
That's the reason why I don't like to talk about it.
People, if you was cooking anything, eating that for yourself,
And if they was hungry, they'd go and eat it all up and get nothing.
They'd just come in and drink up all them milk.
Just do as they please.
Time to be passing by all night long, walking, mudding, raining.
Oh, they had a cold time.
Colored people is free.
They ought to be awful thankful.
And some of them are sorry they are free now.
Some of them never would rather be slaves.
Which would you rather be, Uncle Phil?
Me?
Which I'd rather be?
You know what I'd rather do?
If I thought, had any idea, that I'd ever be a slave again, I'd take a gun and just end it all right away.
Because you're nothing but a dog.
You're not a thing but a dog.
Night never comes out.
You have nothing to do.
Time to cut tobacco.
If they want you to cut all night long out in the field, you cut.
And if they want you to hang all night long, you hang.
Hang tobacco.
It didn't matter about your ties, being tied, you're afraid to say you're tied.
They just, well.
When did you come to Baltimore?
You know, you don't remember when Garfield died, do you?
When they shot Garfield?
No, I don't think he was born.
I don't think so either.
I don't remember what year that was myself now.
But I knew you wasn't born.
When I come to Baltimore that year, I don't remember what year it was now myself.
But if I was laying in the bed, I could remember.
But I don't remember now.
But did you go to work for Mr. Shirley when you came to Baltimore?
Oh, no, no.
I worked for a man by the name of Reed when I first come to Baltimore.
I used to come here to haul manure for him.
All horses were here then.
No electric cars, no cable cars, all horse cars.
And I used to haul manure, go around to different stables.
Everybody had horses for their use when I first come here.
They had coachmen.
Men driving around didn't have automobiles.
They hadn't been there so long.
And then they put on a cable car, what they called cable cars.
Well, they run them for a little while, maybe a couple of three years or four years.
Then somebody invented the electric car, and that first one on North Avenue.
Well, they had it on a while, and they kept on inventing and inventing until
They got them all, different kinds of cars, you know.
There was horse cars.
There wasn't no electric car at all.
There wasn't no big cars like you got now, you know.
I just can't, I just can't think of what year it was.
But,
You're not getting tired, are you, young friend?
No, no, I ain't.
I'm just sitting at home.
It's like I'm sitting in the house.
I was thinking about, oh, now you know how we served the Lord when I was a boy?
We would go to somebody's house and, well, we didn't have no house like we've got now, you know.
We had these, what they call, log cabins.
And they have one old, maybe one old colored man would be there.
Maybe he'd be as old as I am.
And he'd be the preacher.
Not as old as I am now.
He'd be the preacher and we'd all sit down and listen to him talk about the Lord.
Well, he'd say, well, I wonder, sometimes he'd say, I wonder if we'll ever be free.
Well, some of them would say, well, we're going to ask the Lord to free us.
So he'd say, well, we're going to sing.
I wonder, shall I ever reach heaven?
I wonder, shall I fly?
And they would sing that for about an hour
Then the next one would get up and say, let's sing a song.
We're going to live on milk and honey.
Way by and by.
Oh, I can hear them singing now, but I can't repeat like I could in them days.
But someday when I'm not hoarse, I could tell you.
I could sing it for you, but I'm too hoarse now.
And then he would sing.
I'm going to.
I'm going to.
Sing around the order.
Oh, I wish I could sing it for you.
I'm going to sing around the order.
I wish you could, too.
Well, someday you come over here, and I'm not host.
You get me to come up here, and I'll try to sing it for you.
Okay, I'm going to do that.
Now, I heard people here now sing about a rolled shirt and a roll.
Well, that's old-time people.
That's what the old people used to sing in old back days.
The Roll Jordan Roll?
Yeah, but they don't sing it like the old people used to sing it in them days.
They sing it quite different now.
There's another one they sing by and by when the morning comes.
Well, they sing that different, too.
But they're getting the old people's songs.
I hear them come over the radio.
I know them all just as good as they, but they sing them different.
They have different names.
Yes, well, they cut them all short and all they get.
If I had my voice, I would sing this one for you so you'd go in that room, but I can't do it on account of my voice.
But someday you come over here, you come and call me up and let me know how my voice is.
Ever since I took that medicine from that doctor, it hurt my voice.
Now there was a preacher in my house the other night.
He lived right next door to me and he played it on the piano.
And he played something and I sung it for him.
And now he wants me to go down to his church next Sunday.
I told him, I said, now, if I go down to your church, I'll not sing nothing.
Because if I do, I'll get hoarse.
I can't talk.
But he said, Brother Hughes, I don't care whether you sing or not.
I just want you to go down there and let the people see who you are.
Let them see who the old people is.
I said, well, I'll be glad to go down with him.
So next Sunday, I'm going down to his church.
Nothing happened.
But if he sings something old, I...
Just sing along.
I feel the spirit now, but I can't.
I got to keep quiet.
Now, do you ever hear this fellow that comes over the radio?
I think they call him Holmes.
Comes over Sunday night about 12 o'clock on WFPR.
No, I've never heard him or not.
Well, you turn him on.
He comes on the quarter after 11 on Sunday night.
Well, you must have heard him because he says, you can't keep a good man down.
So he makes so much noise, it looked like everybody ought to hear him.
But now when that fellow comes around, I'm laying in the bed.
Don't you know, I get just so, I got to be in that.
Because it's all old time business.
And somebody don't like it.
They says, I don't like homes.
I says, why?
Oh, he says, it makes too much noise.
I said, well, the Bible said make a noise over Jesus.
Jesus said make a noise over me.
So he makes a noise over me.
And I does enjoy certainly show.
Oh, he's, oh, everybody, he's got a big crowd and we just get so happy.
I got to do that too.
Boy, when you feel the grace of God, you got to jump up.
I lay in bed, I got to get up.
Help carry on.
Then next morning I can't talk.
And this is part two of AFS recording number 9,990, original LWL number 1,500, reel number three of three.
The doctor gave me that medicine and just told me all this.
I sure hope you come back again because I'd like to hear you sing.
The old people used to say, wonder if I shall ever reach heaven or wonder shall I fly.
I used to go singing.
Well, sometimes I feel the spirit, you know.
I might get to sing someday again someday.
Do you go to church every Sunday, Uncle Finn?
Don't go to church at all.
I listen to the radio.
Listen to it on the radio, huh?
Because I tell you why I don't go to church.
You'd rather not have this on?
You'd rather not tell me or you'd rather not have this on when you tell me?
It don't make a difference.
I ain't going to say nothing wrong.
I ain't going to say nothing wrong.
This is the B-side of AFS recording number 9986, original LWO number 1559, reel two of three.
